post_text:
Know what's happening in your School District!

On August 19th the Ellensburg Board of Directors Passed their schedule for Board Meetings for the 2020-2021 academic year.

During the 2020-2021 School Year, the Ellensburg School District Board of Directors meet for their "Regular Board Meetings" and for their "Study Sessions" twice a month on Wednesdays. Study Sessions are held at 4:30 prior to the Regular Board Meeting Starting at at 6:00 pm on the same day. Notice of Special Meetings will be posted on the Website and District Calendar. Please note that currently due to COVID-19 all Board Meetings are held virtually.

For more more information about the ESD Board and to view the 2020-2021 calendar, visit the link below.
https://www.esd401.org/about-us/school-board

post_text:
2020 National Association of Agricultural Educators (NAAE):

Samantha (Sammi Jo) Sims, Agricultural instructor at Ellensburg High School has been named the Region I Teachers turn the Key Award. Sammi Jo started her Ag Teaching career in 2017 and has taught a wide variety of agricultural courses including Ag Biology, MS Into to Ag Metals, Natural Resources and ecology, Ag Business and Horticulture. Beau Snow, Ellensburg HS Principal, states “Samantha is a committed educator that consistently seeks opportunities to grow professionally and to help students reach their potential.” And “First and foremost she cares about kids and wants them to be the best they can be. She has demonstrated that she has high expectations for student conduct, and that she is willing to hold students accountable for that conduct,” These statements won’t surprise any of us who have watched her grow up in the Ag Ed Family. Being the daughter of an Ag Teacher ensures that she has the work ethic and determination to be a success. Has her dad might say “Good job youngen”.

June 10 at 1:07 PM ·

*UPDATED JUNE 15*

Great news! FISH heard your feedback and have made changes to their Summer Grab & Go Sites! 18th & Alder and Morgan Middle School have been added.

Thursday, June 18, will be the last day for meal distribution through ESD. Our Grab & Go bags will be "double packed" that day to cover Friday, June 19 as well. There will be no meal distribution on Friday, June 19.

Starting Monday, June 22, FISH Community Food Bank will take over. The good news is the program will be run in much the same way! Meals will be packaged for Grab & Go and FREE to ALL CHILDREN 18 and under.

Ellensburg Sites:
Mt Stuart M-F, 10:45am-12:00pm
North Alder & 18th M-F, 10:45am-12:00pm
Morgan Middle School M-F, 12:15pm-2:00pm
Millpond Manor M-F, 12:15pm-2:00pm

shared_text:
Ellensburg High School
June 4 at 7:43 PM ·

Dear Seniors in the Class of 2020- While we aren't getting to celebrate your graduation in the way we planned just a few short months ago, we still want you to know we couldn't be more proud of you. We are proud of your academic accomplishments. We are proud of your resilience and grace in these unprecedented times.

We are missing being at Nicholson Pavilion at 8 pm tonight, in a sea of blue. We are missing the pomp and circumstance of the ceremony we host in your honor. Tonight, we are missing you.

No matter where we are, we are so proud you are Bulldogs. While it hasn't been the journey we wanted, we are proud to celebrate you over and over, Class of 2020.

Sincerely,

EHS Admin and Staff

Help is available to assist Ellensburg residents pay their rent if they have been adversely impacted due to COVID-19. The city has created a fund with $50,000 as a result of a bill passed by the Washington legislature offering flexibility in allocation of sales tax to housing needs. To apply, visit: https://buff.ly/3a7iBmN

Healthy People, Healthy Economy!

Whether you are shopping at the grocery store or our county's food pantries, these tips are aimed to help keep you and those around you as safe as possible. As more businesses begin to open, we encourage everyone to continue these best practices and keep our county moving in the right direction.

shared_text:
Ellensburg School District Child Nutrition
May 1 at 7:31 AM ·

Today is the DAY! Help us celebrate our School Lunch Heroes by visiting one our meal distribution sites and showing our team a little love. Since schools closed on March 13, we have served nearly 35,000 meals!

Our list of heroes is long...
From our cooks who get here before dawn,
To the helpers who pack hundreds of bags each day,
To the group who load our buses,
To the bus drivers who transport the meals to our sites,
To the servers who greet you with smiles (behind their masks),
To the custodians who keep our kitchens clean...
We could not do this without them. Thank you!

We hope to see you today!
#schoollunchhero #covid19heroes #essentialworkers #schoolfood

Congratulations to the following 10 Ellensburg High School students enrolled in Ms. Price's AP Computer Science A (Java) class, who earned their Microsoft Technology Associate Certificate today in Java. The MTA in Java is an industry recognized certificate and can lead to jobs such as a software engineer, java developer, and web developer. Java is ranked as one of the most popular programming languages and is used by the world's biggest companies to build desktop apps and web systems. Having this certificate gives these students a competitive edge in any career they choose. For some of these students, this is their second Microsoft Technology Associate certificate to add to their resume. Way to go!!!

Mitchell Garcia
Peter Hogan
Nathaniel Brons*
Ethan Price*
Thomas Lonowski*
Isaiah Colwell*
Melissa Lopez-Barbosa*
Garrett Mullings*
Adele Caron*
George Libenow*

* Earned a MTA certificate in Java and Python programming languages

Winning first place in the Yakima Valley region competitions in February and earning berths in the state competition are:

McKenzie Bandy, timpani
Cristian Caballero, tenor saxophone
Logan Cook, trumpet

post_text: Congratulations ESD and EHS! Ellensburg School District earned a position on the 10th Annual AP District Honor Roll. The Annual District Honor Roll recognizes school districts for increasing access to Advanced Placement course work while maintaining or increasing the percentage of students earning scores of 3 or higher on AP Exams. Reaching these goals indicates that our district is successfully identifying motivated, academically prepared students who are likely to benefit from rigorous AP course work. Thank you to all the teachers and staff, whose hard work and dedication made this award possible.

At halftime, the senior royalty will be crowned and then the halftime show will conclude with fireworks sponsored by Alpha Pyrotechnics. During the first half, there will also be fireworks/loud booms for each touchdown scored by the Bulldogs.

WRESTLING: Regional Wrestling at EHS has been cancelled. Our 7 wrestlers will now compete in a 32 man bracket at the Mat Classic in Tacoma next Friday and Saturday.

BOYS BASKETBALL: EHS boys fell to Prosser and will host Wapato tomorrow at EHS with a tentative 5pm start pending weather.

post_text:
We are so proud of our Career and Technical Education (CTE) programs! Please join us in congratulating our EHS FFA students who competed in the national competition in Denver, Colorado last week!

Our EHS FFA Livestock Evaluation team competed at the Western National
Roundup Livestock Judging competition in Denver on Friday. The team
placed third in Beef, third in Sheep, 5th in Goats and also competing
in Swine. When combining all species they placed 6th. Members
competing were Tim Case, McKenzie Basterrechea, Payton Lyyski, Cora
Clift and Craig Burris.

The second picture includes the Washington State 4-H Team with our FFA
Members. All four of those team members are also Kittitas County 4-H
members and three EHS students (Tess Preppernau, Bailey Sherley,
Courtney Bach and former EHS student Kelby Svendson). When you see
them please join us in congratulating them on their achievements!

post_text: October is Cyber Security Month! On Thursday, October 25th at 10:15AM, Ellensburg High School's CyberPatriot Club will host guest speaker Kellon Benson, a 2012 graduate of EHS to speak about his experience as a Security Analyst and to help raise awareness for Cyber Security. Mr. Benson currently works in Central Washington University's Information Security Department, and will be speaking to students about careers in Cyber Security, and will share his experience with incident responses, digital forensics, and network security monitoring. This is an exciting opportunity for students and community members to come listen to a real-life security analyst. EHS now offers Computer Science classes, and students interested in technology careers have joined CyberPatriot, a National Youth Cyber Education Program, to learn how to identify vulnerabilities and strengthen systems to prevent security breaches, giving students a competitive advantage in today's job market.This valuable opportunity to come learn about Cyber Security!

post_text:
Good morning,

Yesterday afternoon we received a phone call and messages on Facebook about an incident on a bus. The Ellensburg School District became aware of this matter Thursday afternoon and is conducting a full and thorough investigation. The outcome of this investigation will be communicated directly with the student's parents. Student safety is paramount to us and we appreciate our community members' concern.

The investigation began immediately and is on going. We appreciate your patience.

MMS 8th grade InterAct Club's just had their year end celebration and there is a LOT to celebrate!

Greg Zemple from Ellensburg Morning Rotary presented the students with the official club charter from Rotary International, as well as individual membership cards. (And pizza!) . Then club members presented 45 pairs of shoes to Dr. Blaise Dondji for children in Bawa, Cameroon, Africa!

These fabulous students hope to get an InterAct Club going at EHS to continue their amazing work!

In an effort to keep our schools a safe and happy place for our students, our school district is launching a new anonymous, 2-way reporting app for students - STOPit. The app encourages students to "See Something, Say Something" and allows them to report:

-Bullying/Cyberbullying
-Violence/Threats
-Hazing
-Weapons Possession
-Drugs/Alcohol
-Substance Abuse
-Intolerance/Discrimination

The app is free for students and allows for two-way communication between them and an administrator. Students can go to the App Store or the Android App on Google Play and search :STOPit. They will see an icon with an S in the middle surrounded by two hands.

---
The Morgan access code is: mmsbulldogs
The EHS access code is: onebigbulldog
---
Watch this video for more information:
shared_text:
STOPIT.VIDS.IO

The Mt. Stuart Parent Group will be holding a silent auction this Friday, April 27th to raise funds to replace damaged playground equipment at Mt. Stuart Elementary. This event will be held in conjunction with a dinner and a dance - and all are invited!

The silent auction includes quite a few exciting items including a 3 night, 2 day fly fishing trip at your choice of three rivers throughout the state, a number of professional paintings and fine art prints from local artists, sports tickets for college, minor league, and major league teams, concert tickets, gourmet coffee beans, several professional photo sessions, a few beautiful quilts, dog training, home video services, gift baskets, and much more.

post_text:
Ellensburg High School earned a fifth place trophy in the 2018 Washington State High School Knowledge Bowl - that extended our annual collection of 2A division state trophies to five!

The students competed against 17 other teams to test their knowledge in a broad range of academic areas, with questions ranging in topics from math and science to history and language arts.

Pictured below left to right: Audrey Piacsek, Ryan Lubinski, James Kirkham, Camille Bruya, Henry Donahue, and Aaron Rosser. And a huge thank you to faculty coach Marco Bicchieri for leading these talented students!

EHS has qualified for the state Knowledge Bowl
tournament for all 13 years that Ellensburg has been involved in the program.

post_text:
In 8th grade Quest, students are tasked with forming engineering firms. Tasks include budgeting, purchasing and designing. The goal? Build a bridge that meets specific length, width, and roadbed requirements.

Students complete this project within the context of a fixed budget, changing prices due to supply and demand as well as chance cards that add opportunities and/or complications along the way.

Bridges are assessed based upon meetings specs, roll and load testing, aesthetic considerations, economic efficiency, as well as structural efficiency.

This video shows the fruits of the Brainy Fools team - view them all on the Ellensburg YouTube Channel!

Have you ever thought, “I wish there was an app for that…?" What if you got to use class time to build that app? You’re in luck! Next fall, Ellensburg High School is offering new classes unlike any you’ve taken before. You’ll learn how to go beyond just using computers—you’ll begin to create the games, apps, and programs you see a need for today!

The best part is that you don’t need any experience to make awesome things in this class - make a game, create an app, or build a web page that your friends, family, and school can use!

What else can you do with computer science? Watch this inspiring video.

No matter what you want to do one day—whether it’s art, medicine, or history—computer science will help you make your ideas come to life.

Students - sign up for INTRO TO PROGRAMMING or email Joell Boast with any questions. (joell.boast@esd401.org)

post_text:
Ellensburg High School was briefly evacuated this morning due to a battery in a custodial closet exploding and creating some fumes which set off the alarm.

Students are back in class, the fumes are contained to the closet area, and we are barricading off the area to avoid any issues.

The building will remain in a passive alarm state so that the HVAC system doesn't circulate the air, and air cleaner/scrubbers are being used to clean the air in the closet. We will turn the HVAC back on as soon as we can confirm the air is clean at the site.

Teachers and staff will remain watchful of any students that are experiencing respiratory issues.

Thank you to our departing School Board Directors, Heather Hazlett and Curtis Bull for your service!

Did you know that you can submit a comment to our school board at https://www.esd401.org/community/school-board? All comments are reviewed at school board study sessions the 2nd and 4th Mondays of each month.

MMS Interact Club would like to invite everyone at our schools and in our community to participate in a district-wide Letters to Santa drive to benefit Make-a-Wish Foundation.

It's simple...just write a letter to Santa by Tuesday, December 12th, return to any school's front office or the district office, and the leaders of MMS Interact Club will pick up the letters for delivery to Santa on Wednesday, December 13th.

EACH LETTER = $1 DONATION BY MACY'S TO THE MAKE-A-WISH FOUNDATION for terminally ill children.

This is a great initiative that we hope everyone will support.

post_text:
Yesterday, a beautiful piece of art honoring Forrest Cross, Morgan Middle School's honored and beloved former head custodian who passed away in 2013 was installed at Morgan Middle School. We were able to commission this work using windows from the old building!

The artist is Austin Harris, a former MMS student and now art major at CWU. We couldn't be more thrilled with his spectacular rendition of the valley that Forrest loved so much and the windows he worked so hard to maintain.
